<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-162-734  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 162 734.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Proceedings of the IEEE  Jan 1989 v77 n1 p210(12).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Distributed routing for load balancing. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Boel, Rene K.; Schuppen, J.H. van.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>One problem in the control of discrete-event systems is how todesign routing units for a queueing network made up of severalservice stations, each of which has its own waiting room, andseveral arrival streams of tasks, each of which has its ownrouting unit.andP;  Considered here are the amount of information eachrouting unit should have available at the time of decision so asto perform well.andP;  Routing units are assumed to make a decision onwhere to send an arriving task at the time of the arrival.andO;Open-loop, or feedforward, polices are compared with simpleclosed-loop, or feedback, policies in which the routing unit atthe time of an arrival can look at only one queue length.andP;  Thelack of online coordination means it is unlikely that an 'optimalpolicy' will be found, but reasonable performance robustness interms of service rate changes is provided.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Load BalancingTheoretical ResearchModels of ComputationDiscrete SimulationEvent-Driven SystemsSystem DesignClosed-Loop SystemsControl SystemsQueueing Networks.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Model of load balancing system with two stations. (chart)The transient behavior of several open-loop policies. (chart)The ergodicity regions for several open-loop policies. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>